{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>Members of this family are generally found near other genes involved in the biosynthesis of a variety of exopolysaccharides. These proteins consist of two fused domains, an N-terminal hydrophobic domain of generally low conservation and a highly conserved C-terminal sugar transferase domain ([interpro:IPR003362]). Characterised and partially characterised members of this subfamily include Salmonella WbaP (originally RfbP) [[cite:PUB00042823]], Escherichia coli WcaJ [[cite:PUB00042825], [cite:PUB00060981]], Methylobacillus EpsB [[cite:PUB00021014]], Xanthomonas GumD [[cite:PUB00042826]], Vibrio CpsA [[cite:PUB00042827]], Erwinia AmsG [[cite:PUB00042828]], Group B Streptococcus CpsE (originally CpsD) [[cite:PUB00042829]], and Streptococcus suis Cps2E [[cite:PUB00042830]]. Each of these is believed to act in transferring the sugar from, for instance, UDP-glucose or UDP-galactose, to a lipid carrier such as undecaprenyl phosphate as the first (priming) step in the synthesis of an oligosaccharide \"block\". This function is encoded in the C-terminal domain. The liposaccharide is believed to be subsequently transferred through a \"flippase\" function from the cytoplasmic to the periplasmic face of the inner membrane by the N-terminal domain. Certain closely related transferase enzymes such as Sinorhizobium ExoY [[cite:PUB00042831]] and Lactococcus EpsD [[cite:PUB00042832]] lack the N-terminal domain and are not identified by this entry.</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure nil, :overlaps-with nil, :member-databases {"ncbifam" {"TIGR03025" "exopolysaccharide biosynthesis polyprenyl glycosylphosphotransferase"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Exopolysaccharide biosynthesis polyprenyl glycosylphosphotransferase", "short" "EPS_sugar_tfrase"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 1, "domain_architectures" 0, "proteome